<br>
Interracial marriage falls under the 14th Amendment for equal protection because the marriage law wouldn't be enacted the same for a black/white male/female couple.  The reason the 14th Amendment applies that the interracial couple are in the same situation as a non-mixed race couple but are being treated differently, meaning they fall under the typical marriage laws in the state but the color of their skin is dictating how they are treated regarding those laws.  It would be the same for barring people to vote because of their race.  <br>
<br>
Pornography is a 1st Amendment issue for the freedom of expression.  The same would be true if the government of a particular state decided what books you could or couldn't read.  Again, a 1st Amendment issue.<br>
<br>
I wasn't saying this ruling was going to lead to people having sex in front of children in the streets, but then again, I'm hardly suprised at your overreaction regarding it.  I said that states regulate that, and they regulate polygamy, and states regulate incest laws as well.  It's a state issue.  If you want to fix the sodomy laws, get your state legislature to repeal them.  If you want Polygamy in your state, get it passed.  If you want to be able to have sex in the street in front of kids, get it passed. If states what to prohibit alcohol, that's up to them.  Personally, I'm not going to try to regulate someone's behavior unless it adversely affects someone else in a <br>
<br>
There are definately times for the Supreme Court to hear cases, I'm just tired of them finding things in a document that clearly don't exist to further their own political agendas (no matter if I agree or disagree with them).  Intrepreting the Constitution because things have changed and the language is cloudy is one thing, intrepreting the document to further your political or social views is another.  <br>
<br>
If that means that some backwoods state doesn't have their citizens get off their ass and fix the obviously broken laws, that's what it means then.  The United States Federal Government wasn't and shouldn't be a centralized entity homogenizing the entire country.  The Constitution is clearly protection AGAINST that happening.  The States are meant to be very different from one another, for a number of reasons including that if a State government gets too tyrannical, you can move to another state that is less tyrannical.  On the other hand, if you make everything a Federal issue, where do you have to go?<br>
<br>
