AND I QUOTE:<br>
<br>
Bill of Rights, Ratified December 15, 1791<br>
<br>
Article IV<br>
<br>
&quot;The right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures, shall not be violated, and no Warrants shall issue, but upon probable cause, supported by Oath or affirmation, and particularly describing the place to be searched, and the persons or things to be seized.&quot;<br>
<br>
No right to privacy?  What does &quot;Secure in their persons, houses, papers and effects&quot; mean to you?<br>
<br>
Just thought I'd mention that.  I realize that Article IV was part of the court's reasoning...but I'd like that cleared up.<br>
<br>
I'm told daily about the &quot;no right to privacy&quot; thing when I have the Bill of Rights framed on my wall, and I dunno about you, but that's how _I_ see Article IV being interpreted.<br>
