If you're going to declare something Unconstitutional, you'd best have Constitutional ground to stand on.  Meaning, if you want to say that the law violated the 1st Amendment right to Freedom of Expression, then say that.  Don't twist the document to mean what you want, read what it says and base it off of that.  The did use the due process clause from the 14th Amendment (by the way that's the 4th Amendment, not article 5) and .  Article five describes the process of amending the Constitution.  If you want to claim that the Court had jurisdiction over this case, you could find that out in Article 3.  <br>
<br>
What you are saying is &quot;The right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects&quot;.  That's dandy... why don't you put the whole sentece in there instead of quoting it out of context?  The whole sentence is <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The right of the people to be secure in their persons, houses, papers, and effects, against unreasonable searches and seizures, shall not be violated, and no warrants shall issue, but upon probable cause, supported by oath or affirmation, and particularly describing the place to be searched, and the persons or things to be seized. <br>
