 <br>
Another note in the declaration is the truth: The law in question was being used in a prejudicial manner- homosexuals were being prosecuted for sodomy,and heterosexual acts of sodomy were not. For example,these two men were charged and convicted. However,a case where a prostitute was caught performing anal sex with a john usually wasn't-the law was being used to punish homosexuality,rather than sodomy.<br>
 <br>
It might have been illegal for some attractive woman to perform fellatio on me in Texas,but the cops sure as heck wouldn't have charged me with sodomy if they busted down my door and found me and my wife in the act. More than likely,they'd have turned around while I got my pants up and apologized for disturbing me!<br>
<br>
Indeed,that was something the Court noted in throwing out precedent in this manner-that the basis of anti-sodomy laws in the US and even beforehand has been to punish people for acts of sodomy with a partner that is being forced to do so,cannot legally consent,or is unable to consent (for example,sodomizing a child,animal,or engaging in an act of sodomy with an unwilling adult of either sex). The Texas law had no such grounds to stand on.<br>
<br>
It was a bad law,and got exactly what it deserved.<br>
