<br>
Yes, the sodomy laws are arbitrary and should not be on the books anywhere.  However, the people of Texas should be the ones to decide the outcome of this law, not the Supreme Court.  <br>
<br>
If the people of Texas want to ban people for, say, smoking on public streets, they should be allowed to do so. Should enough Texans this the law is stupid, it is their responsibility to write their senator.  If enough people write, and the senator ignores them, then said senator will not have another term in office.  <br>
<br>
With this sodomy case, more pressure should have been applied to the DA's office for prosecuting it in the first place.  Also, the DA should have prosecuted the neighbor for lying to the police in their report which justified the search of the couple's home.  <br>
<br>
The concern of us on right side of the spectrum (or myself at least) is not the moral dangers of sodomy. Personally, I couldn't care less about what couples do behind locked doors.  My concern is that we are giving too much power to the Federal Gov't, and taking power away from the State.  Allowing the SC to step outside of its authority is doing a great evil for a greater good, which is something, I'm sorry to say, is not something I'm entirely comfortable with.  Especially when there is a perfectly viable alternative.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jullietstarshooter>julliet starshooter</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/30/03 10:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm62.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=527.topic&index=38>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: It's about time... sodomy laws declared unconstitutional</span><hr size=1> Twotribes:<br>
